  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Way Forward</narrative>
  </title>
  <description>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Rakai district was the first to report HIV in Uganda in 1978. Following a period of stabilization, HIV prevalence is now resurgent. Awareness among young people about HIV is diminishing and stigma prevents people from finding out their status until they are already extremely ill. This project will provide social, health and nutritional care through a volunteer-led, home-based care programme. The local organisations will advocate for expanded testing services and promote the rights of people with HIV and their children to property ownership and education. Households will be supported through counseling, training and material support. Where necessary, foster families will be identified and supported to care for orphans and ensure continued access to education. The programme will include &apos;straight-talk&apos; with families and communities about HIV, support for ARV treatment and adherence, and improve the livelihoods of positive people. The local organisations are a coalition of 25 community-based organisations mostly established as support groups by people living with HIV. This proposal will strengthen the capacity of the lead agency to support a wide range of community partners, volunteers and activists.</narrative>
  </description>
